The target of the 2 Iskander-M strikes on Slovyansk was a temporary deployment point used by Azov (confirmed by locals). This is why it took over 12 hours for official photos to be released, compared to the usual 1-4 hours.  Coordinates: 48.8547272, 37.5837133

Here's footage showing the second Iskander-M ballistic missile strike on Slovyansk, Donetsk Oblast (one previous impact can already be seen to the right of the second).
As I previously reported, the target was a temporary deployment point for Azov, or more specifically, the 3rd separate assault brigade. This was today confirmed by Russian sources who received the recon drone footage. Another example of the exclusive info I provide from time to time not being BS.

Around an hour and a half ago, Israeli media reported that a major "security incident" has occurred in Israeli-occupied Rafah, southern Gaza. 
Reports state that a group of 15-20 heavily armed Palestinian fighters stormed an Israeli position from a tunnel which they dug, firing Anti-tank missiles, RPGs, and heavy machine guns. The fighting lasted for around half an hour, with Palestinian forces reportedly attempting to capture Israeli soldiers. 
Multiple IDF evacuation helicopters evacuated the dead and wounded to hospitals.
MiG-31K airborne. Threat of Kinzhal launches.

Around an hour and a half ago, Israeli media reported that a major "security incident" has occurred in Israeli-occupied Rafah, southern Gaza.   Reports state that a group of 15-20 heavily armed Palestinian fighters stormed an Israeli position from a tunnel‚Ä¶

Update: The attempts to capture the Israeli soldiers failed after the 30 minutes of intense clashes. The attack was supported and coordinated with a mortar unit, which fired on the Israeli positions.
Israeli sources claim that 8 of the ~15 militants were killed, and the rest escaped back into their tunnel. Operations to find them are ongoing, and Israeli artillery shelling was reported in the area. The target unit was the Israeli "Haruv" reconnaissance unit of the 900th "Kfir" Infantry Brigade. Kfir's last known location was in Khan Younis, which lines up with clarified Israeli reports on the location of the attack. 
This is a very rare case of a large cell, supported by another cell from afar, carrying out an attack.
